\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 1. Explain }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 shortcomings of 42010:2011}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  in terms of semiotic triangle:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0     1. All models are representations of engineers\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92 conceptualisations}
\par\pard\plain \ri-16872\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0     1. In MDA, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93models represent reality\u8221\'94 makes the semiotic triangle conflate in a [|model] <\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 [|representation]\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 > [|reality] dimension, }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0     1. This cuts-off the conceptualisation vertex and with that our \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93knowledge about our given remark or doctrine *says* there is\u8221\'94. We have removed the \u8220\'93ontological level\u8221\'94 [@Guarino1994b], and with that, the fact that \u8220\'93terminological competence can be gained by formally expressing the ontological commitment of a knowledge base\u8221\'94 (ibid.)}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0     1. (Meta-)model instantiation, and hence level transition, therefore remains at the Term/Model vertex}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0     1. The CIM models both semantics (Domain Model) and pragmatics (Business Model)}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0     1. Models, including the CIM, are validated in other models, while ontologies are interpreted in their conceptualisation (sets and set theory)}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0     1. Models are ultimately expressed as either Data or Code, both located at the Term/Model vertex.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 1. Clarify that the reciprocity between code and data manifests itself as software semantics}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0     1. The relationship between Data and Code is very closely coupled in order to maintain consistency between each other. Inconsistency results in software malfunction or crashes. Maintaining/controlling that consistency is one of the main goals of MDA/MDE.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0     1. Inconsistency between Code and Data has either pragmatic grounds (i.e., code assumes different reality than data resulting in incorrect operations on the data) or semantic grounds (i.e., data assumes different reality than the code resulting in incorrect data being correctly operated on). }
